      "id": 1,
      "text": "The Long Island Rail Road’s main line arrived in Manorville in July 1844, opening a station originally called St.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1,
        18
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1",
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Manorville,_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "In 1845 stationmaster Seth Raynor shortened the name to Manor, and the post office opened as Manorville on January 31.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        23
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Manorville,_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The Manorville Historical Society, founded in 1984, preserves the town’s past through archives and exhibits.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://museumsdatabase.com/museums/view/20395"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Its library houses books, magazines, and newspapers that chronicle Manorville’s local history.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://museumsdatabase.com/museums/view/20395"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Manorville sits mostly in Brookhaven, with its northeast corner extending into Riverhead.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        27
